* TODO [2026-07-22 Wed] Check documentation
  The documentation is not quite consistent. It has to be checked and
  fixed systematically

* TODO [2026-07-22 Wed] MooX::StricConstructor
  I can't use strict constructors in some projected objects, as currently the
  corresponding tensor calculations initialize arrays of constructors using
  additional parameters, which seems unsafe. I have to construct them
  safely and add the constriction. The suspects are routines in
  Ph::Util such as make_haydock, _haydock_extra, make_greenp, and incarnate_as.
* DONE [2026-05-08 Fri] pod-coverage
  Test all attributes are pod covered
  My current xt/pod-coverage.t doesn't test lazy attributes. I don't
  understand why. Currently, there are many undocumented. I have to
  document them and I would like the tests to help with them.
* DONE [2025-08-02 Sat] firstState
  Check firstState in unretarded spinor calculations
  I use \delta_{G0}/sqrt2 for both the positive and negative parts. My
  guess is that the correct value is to change the sign of the G=0
  contribution, and that it won't affect any result. But for initial fields
  with many G's, it might make a difference. I have to make the
  corresponding changes to the tests also.

  Finally I conjugated the counterpropagating field in spinor
  calculations.

* DONE [2025-04-30 Wed] Field normalization
  - The normalization of the fields is done so that in the usual case
    the field is normalized to the macroscopic field. However, it is
    not clear if it will work when a firstState is given.
  - It should be possible to unnormalize it, so that it corresponds to
    a given external current or external polarization.
  - That was the purpose of the epsL field in LE::NR2::Field. I can
    add ad-hoc methods to the others, but It will be better to think
    it over and do it correctly.
  - If a firstState is given, there should be no need and no use for
    polarization in ...::Field

    I made rawfield methods to return the unnormalized field,
    interpreting the first state as an external polarization.
